set to adopt a Haitian boy when the massive earthquake struck, and
for days, they didn't know if he was alive or dead, and if he did,
whether their adoption would go through.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;

Not Yet Classified &amp;mdash; Haiti&lt;br/&gt;A s the horrific death toll in Haiti has so tragically demonstrated, the primary defense against earthquakes is to have buildings strong enough to withstand their destructive force. It is estimated that at least 150,000 Haitians perished in the magnitude-7.0 temblor and aftershocks that flattened much of Port-au-Prince and surrounding areas on Jan. 12, and it is feared the final death toll will be significantly higher. The vast majority of victims died inside buildings that turned into death traps as they collapsed. &lt;br /&gt; One of the world's most impoverished nations, Haiti has no national building codes and most of its structures were not built to withstand earthquakes. Because wood is scarce in Haiti, most buildings there are constructed of unreinforced cinder blocks and bricks, which have much lower resistance to earthquakes than wood- or steel-framed structures. They have a tendency to break and crumble rather than bend when struck by strong seismic forces. Shacks made of sheet metal, commonplace in Haiti, also fare very poorly in earthquakes.
&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;

Not Yet Classified &amp;mdash; Haiti&lt;br/&gt;
As the world deals with a new disaster in Chile following an 8.8 earthquake, Haiti is still struggling to recover and the death toll continues to climb. &amp;quot;It was death and destruction to a magnitude I don't think we've seen on this earth in a very long time,&amp;quot; said Dr. Raul Ruiz, an emergency physician from Eisenhower Medical Center, who just returned from a medical mission to Haiti. &lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Dr. Ruiz spent three weeks in Haiti, working with the Jenkins, Penn Haitian Relief Organization which delivered supplies, aid and helped treat thousands of patients. Haiti's President estimates the death toll could reach up to 300,000 people. And over a month since the quake, Dr. Ruiz says public health problems are far from over.&amp;nbsp; &amp;quot;With rainy season coming ahead, we're going to have another disaster in Haiti.&amp;quot;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;

Major areas of concern include sanitation and food distribution. &amp;quot;This is the first time in my life I saw desperate hunger, where you could see the instinct of survival in the eyes of people who would do anything to grab a small bag of rice so their children and family could survive for another week.&amp;quot;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;And while Chile or the United States doesn't have the extreme poverty of Haiti, he says more work must still be done in preparing for a disaster closer to home. &amp;quot;Our emergency rooms are working at capacity, and, at times, over capacity in the winter months,&amp;quot; said Dr. Ruiz. &amp;quot;we need to look at how our emergency rooms are functioning..are we ready for the big one?&amp;quot;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Dr. Ruiz will share more about his medical mission during a concert to raise money for the &amp;quot;Save the Children, Haiti Earthquake Children Emergency Fund.&amp;quot; It will take place at 6:30 at Hotel Zoso, on 150 N. Indian Canyon, in Palm Springs. The concert will feature local artists including Pat Rizzo, Elizabeth Dreyfuss, Dela Zimmer and Bill Marx. &lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
